divisible good auctions with constrained bidding theory empirics and test for common values siepr siepr stanford institute for economic policy research search the site enter your keywords main links home about siepr research at siepr centers programs projects education at siepr events at siepr people at siepr publications at siepr economics in the news support siepr contact us stay connected stay connected home research at siepr research project divisible good auctions with constrained bidding theory empirics and test for common values title divisible good auctions with constrained bidding theory empirics and test for common values principal investigator jakub kastl dates march 1 2008 february 28 2011 sponsor national science foundation my project consists of three closely related parts in the first part i derive theoretical results that are largely motivated by empirical facts documented in recent literature i highlight the departures of the model with restricted bidding strategies from the benchmark with unrestricted strategies then i provide two empirical applications the first one stresses the need to pay close attention to restrictions on bidders strategies when conducting counterfactuals by demonstrating that one might obtain different predictions when using the model without incorporating the bidding restrictions and the second one proposes a new test that distinguishes between common and private valuation paradigms stanford university economics department stanford center for international development public policy program site map economic summit
